That can help insulin resistance but insulin resistance is not the only cause of diabetes. Nor can diet control that fully. Every diabetic is different. You have to find what affects your levels most. For some that is specific foods, not just sugar but also breads, pasta, and potatoes. I know one diabetic who is overly sensitive to the sugars in corn. For some of us exercise is a major factor. For years it didn't really matter what I ate as long as I walked a mile twice a day. Later after I became disabled (for other reasons) and could no longer walk far without major pain, I found Glucoscript and that controlled my insulin resistance for years. Then I developed a health issue that affected my glucagon levels, forcing my sugars up again for an entirely different reason. Your stress level can affect your glucose levels, and so can changes in your sleep. It can be complicated. There is no one-size-fits-all solution. It's sad that too many do not get a thorough education in diabetes when they are diagnosed. \n\nBut by god, the cessation of insulin price gouging would help us make amazing progress.             "channelId": "UCMtFAi84ehTSYSE9XoHefig",
            "videoId": "1kYxb9hfPCQ",
            "textDisplay": "What is truly horrifying about the whole school vs guns thing is as follows:  My school days were NOTHING like this.  We had unlocked doors, no guards, no metal detectors, no armed guards, no lockdown drills, no armed teachers. None of that. Just going to school (mine was a large public school with over 3000 students/approx. 35 per class), doing the usual school activities and sports, and never once do I recall the subject of guns ever coming up.  NOT ONCE. Isn't that what people want for their kids?  A learning environment, concentrating on preparing kids for the future, instead of a tense potential killing field?  WTF?  Kids have somehow become political acceptable losses when it comes to discussing guns.  Somebody please explain to me how it has become "normal" to let politicians convince us that this kind of insanity is acceptable in any way??!!\u003cbr\u003e\u003cbr\u003eNO child should ever walk into a school worried even the tiniest bit that some mental nut job is going to come in with an over-powered firearm and "cut the grass".  No gun, or privilege to own a gun is worth the terror, the bloodshed, the loss, the soul-tearing damage those kids and families in Texas are going through right now. Stop for a minute to imagine being one of those students in that situation, seeing some of your classmates and friends twist in the air as a bullet from a military style weapon rips through flesh and clothing. They stumble and fall around you, dropping books and cellphones, and hitting the floor hard; pools of red blood expanding outward from the bodies of children, their limbs splayed like puppets whose strings were cut.             "channelId": "UCJ0uqCI0Vqr2Rrt1HseGirg",
            "videoId": "cW9bmpy-lTI",
            "textDisplay": "I'm sorry to use THIS comment section to bring this up, I should be talking about James, the video, or all the dedicated people who've worked on this show for years. But I need to say it.\n\nNo one deserves to be cancelled here. I've been an ARMY for ages, I've gone to and graduated from college while getting comfort from their music and content, and I get an unbelievable ammount of strength from them touching on topics that I struggle with daily. I've gained something valuable and positive from being in this fandom. But some parts of it will always make you realize why not everyone sees that positivity from the outside.\n\nEvery fandom has their toxic side. EVERY fandom has a portion of it that loves looking for things to be outraged about, and to rage against, and those people tend to also have a more active, vocal presence on social media. It's just that when the fandom is large, so then do the numbers of such people increase. It becomes harder even for people within the same fandom who happen to disagree with them to speak up against such a large disgruntled mob, especially for people who tend to be more passive and stay away from topics like this, instead just waiting for things to blow over.\n\nI understand where the frustration comes from, and where the feeling of \"righteousness\" comes frombut that doesn't mean they are justified in this case. I've tried reasoning with people on every IG post I find regarding this, and the responses varied a lot as expected, because \"ARMY\" are just people too; some of them  would delete my comments, some of them blocked me, some of them hadn't even heard of this and were getting distorted 2nd hand information, and they would be open to changing their minds when presented with the actual facts.\n\nBut what I also found was a huge number of ARMYs who disagreed with what the fandom was doing.Their opinions on the matter differed a bit from person to personbut they were all speaking up to condemn this behavior. That made me a little more hopeful. It shouldn't be surprising, because most of the people I know in this fandom DO stand for kindness, understanding, and self-betterment, and this is a fandom that consistently uses its passionate power for great causes around the world rather than rash \"cancellations\". But sometimes when things get out of hand like this, it can be easy to forget...\n\nHope this whole thing blows over. Hope this show keeps up the amazing work, hope BTS don't suffer too greatly because of this (they really don't deserve it), and hope ARMYs can still proudly refer to themselves as such moving forward. And to the ones who actually built up a lot of anger, frustration and hatred from this situation, I hope you can find a way to work through these feelings as well, I mean this in the least cynical, condescending or sarcastic way possible.",
            "textOriginal": "I'm sorry to use THIS comment section to bring this up, I should be talking about James, the video, or all the dedicated people who've worked on this show for years. But I need to say it.\n\nNo one deserves to be cancelled here.             "videoId": "9p0L4GRt7zw",
            "textDisplay": "https://www.facebook.com/A.Zeckenbiss/\n First, the ticks ingest the virus with the blood of infected animals, and the virus can then survive for a long time in the tick's digestive tract.  If the tick now bites a person or another susceptible mammal, it can be transmitted through the tick's saliva.  However, transmission can also occur directly through contact with the blood or meat of sick animals.  The virus can be transmitted from person to person through infected urine, feces, saliva, or infected blood.  Droplet infections or aerosols are also possible.  The more severe the disease, the more viruses are excreted by the patient.  Therefore, nosocomial infections also occur to a notable extent.\n\n The incubation period is usually between one and 13 days.  The symptoms set in suddenly: fever (constant for five to twelve days, biphasic course), chills, irritability, headache, muscle pain and aching limbs.  Upper abdominal pain, nausea and vomiting.  Facial reddening and edema, conjunctival and throat reddening are typical.\n\n In some of the patients, a hemorrhagic course develops as a complication from the third to fifth day: intestinal bleeding, vomiting of blood (hematemesis), skin bleeding (up to ecchymosis, small-scale bleeding), hemorrhagic diathesis.\n\n The lethality (mortality) depends on the virus strain and is between two and 50 percent.  It is estimated that about every fifth case in the states of the former USSR is accompanied by hemorrhagic symptoms.  The disease can also be symptom-free (inapparent).  Death usually occurs in the second week of the disease, the cause of death is multiple organ failure.\n\n When the flu outbreaks, the number of actual deaths exceeds that expected.  In this way, around 30,000 additional deaths were determined in Germany for the winter season 1995/96 and the number of 29,000 cases for the winter season 2012/2013.  However, since the turn of the millennium there have also been eight winters with no verifiable excess mortality.\n\n Respiratory syncytial virus (RSV) infections can also overlap with influenza waves.  A study from the US suggests that there are significantly more deaths from influenza in this case;  the excess mortality from influenza is three times higher than that from RSV.\n\n Parainfluenza is caused by various human parainfluenza viruses from the Paramyxovirus family (scientifically Paramyxoviridae) (genera Respirovirus and Orthorubulavirus).  The viruses cause flu-like symptoms.  The infection rate in children up to ten years of age is 90%.  The viruses are spread all over the world.  The transmission occurs through droplet infection.\n\n Parainfluenza often leads to a bacterial superinfection.  The course of the infection depends strongly on the disposition, constitution and especially the age of onset.\n\n Measles or morbilli are highly contagious infectious diseases that mainly affect children.  In addition to the typical red patches of skin (measles rash), the disease causes fever and a considerably weakened general condition.  This so-called childhood disease is caused by the measles virus and in some cases can be life-threatening due to severe progress (complications) with pneumonia and brain infections.\n\n The measles virus occurs worldwide, with the incidence of the disease varying greatly.  Local measles epidemics with high disease and mortality rates occur time and again, particularly in developing countries.  Measles is one of the most common infectious diseases there.  The WHO estimates that they caused nearly half of the 1.7 million vaccine-preventable deaths in children in 2000, out of an estimated 30 to 40 million cases that year.  The number of reported illnesses is far below these estimated values \u200b\u200bdue to the high number of unreported cases\n\n Between September 1998 and April 1999, 229 cases of severe febrile encephalitis were officially reported in Malaysia, and shortly after the epidemic began, nine cases were also reported in Singapore.  Symptoms of severe respiratory infection were also reported here.  Mostly men who worked in slaughterhouses were affected;  48% of the sick died.  It was therefore quickly assumed that there was an association with an infection in animals.  At the same time, a mild outbreak of a febrile respiratory tract infection with unknown pathogen was registered in Malaysia in pigs, which was later identified as the same pathogen as in the encephalitis patients.  In order to prevent the further spread of the epidemic in humans, more than a million pigs were culled, which corresponded to about half of the entire Malaysian pig population.\n\n The infection is easily passed on to humans through close contact with pigs.  Workers in slaughterhouses and on pig farms are therefore considered to be a risk group.  Human-to-human transmission is also possible, as almost half of the workers who fell ill in 1998 had infected a family member.  In pigs, the infection manifests as a mild, febrile respiratory infection.  Pig deaths have not been reported.  Once the infection has been overcome, the pigs appear to be immune to renewed infection;  a corresponding vaccine for pigs has meanwhile been developedbut it is not yet produced or approved.\n\n The very likely biological reservoir of the Nipah virus are fruit bats of the genus Pteropus.  After only serological evidence was found at first, the pathogen could be detected directly in the urine of a flying fox of the species Pteropus lylei in Thailand in 2007.  The infection of the pigs probably originates from these flying foxes through a transmission path which has not yet been fully clarified.  There is evidence that humans can become infected with their saliva and urine through contact with the fruit bats.  Fruits eaten by bats, which in turn are consumed by mammals or humans, pose a high risk of infection.\n\n The disease in humans begins after an incubation period of less than two weeks with acute encephalitis with fever, headache and dizziness.  In 75% of patients, abnormal findings of viral infection in the cerebrospinal fluid appear early.  Patients become comatose within 24 to 48 hours.  Depending on the outbreak, around 40 to 75% of the diseases described so far were fatal.  The administration of ribavirin reduced the mortality to 36%.  In addition to the acute illness, there is also a recurrence of encephalitis in 7.5% of patients, and focal encephalitis only after months in those infected with no symptoms (3.4%).  The time span between acute illness and late complication (relapse) averages 8.4 months.  Permanent damage such as chronic seizure disorders (epilepsy) and personality changes after surviving infection are described.\n\n HCoV-NL63 has its origins in coronaviruses from infected musangs and bats.  HCoV-NL63 is one of seven known representatives of the Coronaviridae that infect humans, including HCoV-229E, HCoV-OC43, HCoV-HKU1, MERS-CoV, the original SARS-CoV (i.e. SARS-CoV-1)  and SARS-CoV-2.  It is estimated that the last common ancestor with HCoV-229E existed about 1000 years ago;  it has probably been circulating in humans for centuries.,\n\n HCoV-NL63 is believed to spread through direct person-to-person transmission in densely populated areas.  The virus particles can survive outside the human body in aqueous solutions at room temperature for up to a week and on dry surfaces for up to three hours.  Most people will contract a coronavirus at some point in their lifebut some segments of the population are more prone to HCoV-NL63.  These include children under the age of 5, the elderly, and the immunocompromised.  HCoV-NL63 appears to have a seasonal preference; in temperate climates it is most common in the winter months.  In more extreme and tropical climates, the virus has no preference for a particular time of year.  Many studies have reported the coexistence of HCoV-NL63 with other human coronaviruses, influenza A viruses, human orthopneumoviruses (human respiratory syncytial virus, hRSV), parainfluenza viruses, and human metapneumoviruses (hMPV).",
